.SH NAME
.PP
\f[B]ldif2json\f[R] \[em] converts LDIF format to JSON
.SH SYNOPSIS
.PP
ldif-command | \f[B]ldif2json\f[R] [\f[B]options\f[R]]
.PD 0
.P
.PD
\f[B]ldif2json\f[R] [\f[B]options\f[R]] LDIF-file [ LDIF-file \&... ]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.PP
Reads LDAP Data Interchange Format (LDIF) from standard input or files
passed as arguments and writes tabular JSON to standard output.
One JSON object is written per line.
By default if an attribute is a valid number for all input records, it
is coerced to a number on output.
.SS Options
.TP
-h, \[en]help
Prints brief usage information.
.TP
-f, \[en]flatten
By default all attribute values are arrays of values, even if only one
value is present.
This option converts attributes to single values if all values across
all records contain only a single value.
Not compatible with \[en]join
.TP
-jSEP, \[en]join=SEP
instead of outputting arrays, output single strings joined by the
separator SEP
.TP
-t ATTRIBUTE:TYPE, \[en]type=ATTRIBUTE:TYPE
For the attribute ATTRIBUTE interpret it as the type TYPE
.RS
.PP
Valid values for TYPE are: \[lq]auto\[rq] (the default - if all values
are valid numbers then coerce to a number, otherwise a string),
\[lq]string\[rq], \[lq]number\[rq] (convert to a number and exit with an
error if any attribute values are not valid numbers) and
\[lq]number0\[rq] (convert to a number or 0 for values that are not
valid numbers)
.RE
.SH EXAMPLES
.IP
.nf
